**Version Used**:  5.5.0-2.26168.11 (02860c0c203c43a43487ae6a353600a4e5505bcf)

**Steps to Reproduce**:

1. Create a method that returns a `struct` type, with a valid `Deconstruct()` method.
2. Define the `struct` type to contain pointers.
3. Attempt to explicitly deconstruct the returned `struct`.

```csharp
unsafe
{
    (int* a, int* b) = Method(); // CS1525

    var(a, b) = Method(); // No error
}

static Deconstructable Method() => new();

public unsafe struct Deconstructable
{
    int* A, B; // Any T*

    public void Deconstruct(out int* a, out int* b)
    {
        a = A; b = B;
    }
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**: `"CS1525: Invalid expression term 'T'"`

**Expected Behavior**: Type name `T*` is parsed in full, and both deconstructions succeed.

**Actual Behavior**: Only `T` is parsed, ignoring the `*` token, and resulting in CS1525.

### Description

 When a library provides both `Task<T>` and `ValueTask<T>` overloads of the same generic extension method, the 
compiler reports CS0121 (ambiguous call) when the argument is an async lambda or method group — even though the 
return type of the lambda/method unambiguously matches only one overload.

 ### Reproduction

 ```csharp
 public static class Extensions
 {
     // Task overload
     public static async Task<string> BindAsync<T>(this T value, Func<T, Task<string>> func)
         => await func(value);

     // ValueTask overload
     public static async ValueTask<string> BindAsync<T>(this T value, Func<T, ValueTask<string>> func)
         => await func(value);
 }

 public class Example
 {
     static Task<string> GetNameAsync(int id) => Task.FromResult($"Name-{id}");

     public async Task Demo()
     {
         // CS0121: The call is ambiguous between:
         //   Extensions.BindAsync<int>(int, Func<int, Task<string>>)
         //   Extensions.BindAsync<int>(int, Func<int, ValueTask<string>>)
         var result = await 42.BindAsync(id => GetNameAsync(id));

         // Workaround: explicit Func<> cast
         var result2 = await 42.BindAsync((Func<int, Task<string>>)(id => GetNameAsync(id)));
     }
 }
```

Expected Behavior

The compiler should resolve `id => GetNameAsync(id)` to the `Func<int, Task<string>>` overload, because `GetNameAsync`
returns `Task<string>`, not `ValueTask<string>`.

Actual Behavior

CS0121 — the compiler considers both overloads equally valid and reports an ambiguous call.

Impact

This pattern is common in Railway Oriented Programming (ROP) libraries and fluent pipeline APIs that provide both 
Task and ValueTask variants for performance. The workaround — casting to an explicit `Func<>` — breaks fluent chains
and is non-obvious to consumers:

```cs
 // What users want to write:
 await account.ToResult()
     .BindAsync(acc => PerformChecksAsync(acc))    // CS0121
     .TapAsync(acc => SaveAsync(acc));              // CS0121

 // What they have to write:
 await account.ToResult()
     .BindAsync((Func<Account, Task<Result<Account>>>)PerformChecksAsync)
     .TapAsync((Func<Account, Task>)(acc => SaveAsync(acc)));
```

Environment

 - .NET 10, C# 14
 - Also reproducible on .NET 8/9, C# 12/13

When a local tool has `"rollForward": true` in `dotnet-tools.json` (or `--allow-roll-forward` is passed), repeated options like `--var a --var b` were silently deduplicated before being forwarded to the tool — only the first `--var` survived.

## Root cause

`MuxerCommandSpecMaker.CreatePackageCommandSpecUsingMuxer` used `Enumerable.Except` to strip `--allow-roll-forward` from the forwarded args. `Except` is a **set operation** — it deduplicates the source sequence as a side effect, collapsing all repeated arguments.

## Fix

Replace `Except` with a `Where` predicate that filters only `--allow-roll-forward` entries:

```csharp
// Before — silently deduplicates all args
arguments.AddRange(commandArguments.Except(rollForwardArgument));

// After — removes only --allow-roll-forward, preserves duplicates
arguments.AddRange(commandArguments.Where(arg =>
    !arg.Equals("--allow-roll-forward", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase)));
```

A test is added to `ToolRunCommandTests` verifying that `--var a --var b` survives the forwarding pipeline intact when `rollForward` is active.

`dotnet nuget add source --help` (and all nuget subcommand help) showed the generic System.CommandLine help for the `nuget` command instead of forwarding to the NuGet CLI. Regression in 11.0 SDK.

## Root Cause

`DotnetHelpBuilder.Write()` used this guard to detect NuGet commands:

```csharp
if (command.GetRootCommand() is NuGetCommandDefinition)
```

`GetRootCommand()` traverses all the way to the actual CLI root (`DotNetCommandDefinition`), so this check is always `false`. The code falls through to `base.Write(context)`, showing the generic System.CommandLine help for the `nuget` command.

## Fix

Replace the broken check with a proper ancestor traversal:

```csharp
if (IsInNuGetCommandTree(command))

private static bool IsInNuGetCommandTree(Command command)
{
    if (command is NuGetCommandDefinition) return true;
    if (command.Parents.FirstOrDefault(p => p is Command) is Command parent)
        return IsInNuGetCommandTree(parent);
    return false;
}
```

This correctly handles all cases:
- Unregistered subcommands like `nuget add source` (where the matched command is `NuGetCommandDefinition` itself, with unmatched tokens)
- Registered direct subcommands (`NuGetDeleteCommandDefinition`, etc.)
- Deeply nested subcommands (`NuGetTrustAuthorCommandDefinition`, etc.)
